Based on the result by Gyárfás and Lehel (1995), for any finite set $A \subset \mathbb{R}$ such that every 4-element subset has 11 differences (which corresponds to exactly 5 distinct positive differences), there exists a Sidon subset $S \subseteq A$ of size at least $|A|/2$. Moreover, this constant $1/2$ is best possible. Thus, the supremum of admissible numbers is $1/2$.

```lean
@[category research open, AMS 5]
theorem erdos_757 {A : Set ℝ} :
    answer(sorry) = sSup {c | IsAdmissible c} := by
  trans (1 / 2 : ℝ)
  · rfl
  · sorry
```
