An admissible set $A$ is a finite set of real numbers where every 4-element subset has exactly 5 distinct differences. This property is quite restrictive. Gyárfás and Lehel [GyLe95] proved that such sets must have a specific structure, essentially being subsets of two arithmetic progressions with the same common difference. For such sets, the size of the largest Sidon subset is at least $|A|/2$. The conjecture (Erdős Problem 757) suggests that $1/2$ is the optimal constant, and indeed constructions of size 6 (e.g., specific subsets of the described structure) show that the ratio $|S|/|A|$ can be exactly $1/2$ (for example, a set of size 6 with max Sidon subset size 3). Therefore, the supremum of admissible $c$ is $1/2$.

